Psychological considerations in the dietary management of patients with DGBI.
In this paper, an expert team of 2 gastro-psychologists, a dietician and an academic gastroenterologist provide insights into the psychological and social implications of evidence-based and "popular" dietary interventions in disorders of gut-brain interaction (DGBI). We focus on practical approaches for evaluating a patient's appropriateness for a dietary intervention, considering the nutritional, psychological, behavioral and social context in which a patient may find themselves managing their DGBI with dietary intervention. We also discuss how to identify risk factors for and symptoms of avoidant-restrictive food intake disorder (ARFID), a growing concern in the DGBI population.
